         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">24/7/90 ¶  ¶ The Bassia Tatei, dear Professor, remains firm in all the specimens; so it has gone at once to the lithographer. ¶  ¶ Kindly look over your species of Corysanthes carefully, to see, wheth...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">90.07.24</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Ralph Tate</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">Barr Smith Library, University of Adelaide, South Australia.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">24/7/90</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The <name key="Bassia%20Tatei">Bassia Tatei</name>, dear Professor, remains firm in all the specimens; so it has gone at once to the lithographer.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See M to R. Tate, 18 July 1890. M described <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Bassia tatei</seg> in B90.09.02; it was depicted in B91.13.24, plate LXXI. After the specimen had been drawn, M returned it to Tate with M to R. Tate, 30 July 1890 (in this edition as 90-07-30a).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Kindly look over your species of Corysanthes carefully, to see, whether you have more than one species. Bentham doubts, whether the specimens, referred by him to C. fimbriata, do really all belong to it. On renewed scrutiny I now find, that on the 16. Sept 1848 I collected on the eastern basis of the Barossa-Range<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">SA.</p>
               </note> a solitary specimen of what seems C. unguiculata. This one plant is however so shrivelled, that I cannot make sure of it, and I do not like, to destroy it in dissection. C. unguiculata has usually the leaves as red underneath as <name key="Acianthus">Acianthus</name>, while the lower page of C. pruinosa is pale-green.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I hope you will gather specimens with <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">ripe</hi>
               </seg> fruit of the two closely allied forms of <name key="Hypoxis">Hypoxis</name>, so that our friendly dispute about them may be settled.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See M to R. Tate, 6 July 1890. </p>
               </note> I am a sceptic about <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">species</hi>
               </seg>, based on very light characteristics. Darwinism leads to Jordanism.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">The French botanist A. Jordan was a notorious splitter of species.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I hope you are now quite strong again.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Have you found any difficulties in sorting out <name key="Helipterum%20hyalospermum">Helipterum hyalospermum</name> and H. Jesseni?</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
